{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}<!--for such a short article, there sure are a lot of sentences without citations--> {{infobox artifact |name = The Hinton St Mary Mosaic |image =[[File:Mosaic2 - plw.jpg|220px]] |image_caption = |material = Ceramic |size = |writing = |created = early 4th century |period = [[Romano-British]] ([[Christianity in Roman Britain|Christian]]) |place = [[Hinton St Mary]] villa, [[Dorset]] |location = G49/wall, [[British Museum]], London |id = |registration = {{British-Museum-db|1965,0409.1|id=808670}} }}
The '''Hinton St Mary Mosaic''' is a large, almost complete [[Roman mosaic]] discovered at [[Hinton St Mary]], [[Dorset]], [[England]]. It appears to feature a [[portrait]] [[Bust (sculpture)|bust]] of [[Jesus|Jesus Christ]] as its central [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]]. The mosaic was chosen as Object 44 in the [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[A History of the World in 100 Objects]]'', presented by [[British Museum]] director [[Neil MacGregor]].
The mosaic covered two rooms, joined by a small decorated threshold. It is largely red, yellow and cream in colouring. On stylistic grounds it has been dated to the 4th century and is attributed to the mosaic workshop of [[Durnovaria]] (modern [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]]). It is currently in storage at the [[British Museum]], although the central medallion is on display there.
==Christian panel== [[File:Roundel mosaic christ hinton st mary british museum edit.JPG|thumb|right|Detail of central roundel mosaic]] The panel in the larger room is {{convert|17|by|15|ft}}. A central circle surrounds a portrait bust of a man in a white [[pallium]] standing before a [[Christian]] [[Labarum|chi-rho]] symbol flanked by two [[pomegranate]]s. He is generally identified as Christ, although the [[Roman Emperor|Emperor]] [[Constantine I]] has also been suggested.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Moorhead|first1=Sam|last2=Stuttard|first2=David|title=The Romans who Shaped Britain|publisher=Thames & Hudson|year=2012|page=203|isbn=978-0-500-25189-8}}</ref> There is much evidence to lead to the identification of this as Christ, not least the absence of any insignia or identifiers pointing to a particular emperor. On each side of this are four [[lunette]]s, each featuring conventional forest and [[hunting]] vignettes, mostly of a dog and a deer. In the corners are four quarter circles containing portrait busts, either representing the [[Anemoi|winds]] or the [[season]]s.
==Pagan panel== The panel in the smaller room is {{convert|16+1/2|by|8|ft}}. It consists of a central circle containing an image of characters from [[Roman mythology]], [[Bellerophon]] killing the [[Chimera (mythology)|Chimera]]. This has been interpreted in a more Christian context as representing good defeating evil. Flanking this are two rectangular panels again featuring dogs hunting deer.
==Context== The mosaic was discovered on 12 September 1963 by the local [[blacksmith]], Walter John White.{{sfn|Toynbee|1964|p=7}} It was cleared by the [[Dorset County Museum]]{{sfn|Toynbee|1964|p=7}} and lifted for preservation by the [[British Museum]],{{sfn|Painter|1967|pp=21–22}} although none of the rest of the building has been examined. It is generally assumed to have been a [[Roman villa|villa]]. The layout of the mosaic room certainly resembles a Roman ''[[triclinium]]'', or dining room. However, it might easily be a [[Church (building)|church]] or other Christian complex. There were no finds dated earlier than {{circa|270}}.
